So in the case that you're developing an interactive story that progresses bit by bit between both participants [I was having it Game Master a 1 player Pathfinder session for me] then it is reading the old material every time it generates new material.

By the second day just the background information I was starting each scene with was over 700 characters, and by the end of the scene it was getting close to the 4,000 character limit before I would clear the scene, add minimal context to the background information and begin the next scene.

ChatGPT unswer: 

GPT-3 (Generative Pretrained Transformer 3) and ChatGPT are both large language models developed by OpenAI, but they have different capabilities and are optimized for different tasks.

GPT-3 is the third generation of the GPT series of models and is one of the largest language models to date with over 175 billion parameters. It has been trained on a massive amount of text data from the internet and can generate human-like text, perform a wide range of natural language processing tasks such as text generation, question-answering, machine translation, and more.

ChatGPT is a fine-tuned version of GPT-3 specifically for conversational AI and can generate human-like responses in a conversation. While ChatGPT has the ability to perform some of the tasks that GPT-3 can perform, it is specifically optimized for conversational AI and has been fine-tuned to produce more coherent and appropriate responses in a conversational setting.

In terms of comparison, it is not accurate to say that one is better than the other, as it depends on the specific use case and the task the model is being used for. Both GPT-3 and ChatGPT are state-of-the-art models and offer exceptional performance in their respective domains.

Anyway, here's how it went down:

Promt:
write a google sheets formula that scrapes the title form the website in column A

Response:
The formula to scrape the title of a website in Google Sheets is:

=IMPORTXML(A1,"//title")

This formula uses the IMPORTXML function, which is used to scrape data from a webpage. The first argument is the URL of the webpage (in this case, the URL is in cell A1), and the second argument is the XPath of the element you want to scrape (in this case, the title element).

It's important to note that the website URL must allow to be scraped, otherwise, it will give an error in formula. And also some website uses bot prevention techniques, in that case, it will also give error.

Chat GPT > GPT 3  for usage as a tool.

GPT 3 is meant to be fine tuned to make applications like Chat GPT, DialoGPT, ChatSonic

Chat GPT is a fine tuned(specifically trained) with both supervised learning and reinforcement learning.
-Meant to read inputs and generate responses that sound natural and human (slang, acronyms, hyperboles, metaphors, idioms)
-Only has 20 billion parameters to increase accuracy as a chatbot.
-Best at the tasks it was meant to do and learns to perfet them.

GPT 3 is 175 billion parameters of data that is not fine tuned or tailored for a specific usage. 
-Able to perform a larger range of tasks
-Very powerful
-Not as good for chatbot applications.
-Data is HUGE but disorganized.

One of the changes that already touch my work as a programmer is I read code even more instead of writing it. ChatGPT and GPT3 work for me like assistants that can write simple parts of the code. I need just to think about what small parts I need to be written and they deliver in seconds. I still need to read that code and sometimes there are mistakes or refinements to be made, but it's quicker than I would write it. I think more about bigger picture and how to divide it to smaller parts and write less as a programmer. I feel like things take less time than if I would write code on my own but I don't have any calculations. I don't think this is a few times faster development but it feels like about 30% - 50% faster. If you divide things in a smart way into small simpler functions then there are not many bugs in code written by AI.

What I find better in ChatGPT than GPT3 or Github Copilot is that ChatGPT is more like a discussion. You can write it what needs to be fixed/refined in previous code or in a fragment of it and it will try to fix it (more often than not successfully). It will also give insight into errors from the code being run. GPT3 seems better in coding but it is less interactive for me. GPT3 also tries to guess what to add more to the code rather than finishing only what I asked for.

Both are not very good at writing automated tests. They can, but they usually write repetitive tests that cover only the simplest cases (or sometimes only permutations of 1 case).
I usually use them to write one dummy test and then add more tests on my own based on that.

What's the difference between GPT chat and GPT playground

GPT Chat is an online platform for creating and sharing conversations with AI agents powered by OpenAI's GPT-3 natural language processing model. It allows users to generate AI-powered conversations with the model, using a simple chat interface. GPT Playground is a web-based tool that allows users to explore and interact with OpenAI's GPT-3 model by writing prompts and examining the model's generated responses. GPT Playground also provides a visual representation of the model's responses, and allows users to modify the output by changing the underlying parameters of the model.

To calculate a person's carbon footprint in Google Sheets, you can use the SUM function to add up the emissions from various sources and convert them to CO2e using conversion factors.
You could use the following formula to calculate the total CO2e emissions in column D:

=SUM(B1C1:B3C3)

This formula will multiply each emissions value (column B) by its corresponding conversion factor (column C) and add up the results to give you the total CO2e emissions in column D.

You can also use SUMIF function if you have multiple sheet or multiple range of data, so that you can sum the data range accordingly.
